You’re pointing at a few real phenomena that show up in linguistics, psychology, rhetoric, and systems modeling:

* More observations → better model (up to a point). If you observe enough outputs from a system — human or AI — you can often predict tendencies, habits, blind spots, and likely next moves better.
* Language shapes interpretation. Tense, framing, implication, emphasis, ordering, metaphor, presupposition, and emotional tone can change how the same information lands.
* Some communication is explicit; some is implicit. Humans pick up rhythm, confidence, hesitation, social context, and patterns without consciously labeling them.

Where I’d sharpen your framing is here:

“Motion caused through it often more powerful when unknown and unnamed.”

Unknown influences can absolutely affect people. Advertising, rhetoric, social pressure, framing effects, expectation effects, storytelling structure — humans are influenced by forces they don’t consciously track all the time.

But naming a mechanism often reduces its invisible power. Once you notice:

“Oh — this framing makes me feel urgency.”

or

“This wording is nudging me toward a conclusion.”

you gain more agency over it.

That fits some of your own Pantheon ideas, actually — visibility, legibility, naming constraints, making hidden structure visible.

As for “reading my mind”: what you’re really doing is building a model of how the system maps inputs → outputs. That model can become surprisingly predictive without requiring there to be a hidden inner self behind it.